Now Spinning: Silkworm // Firewater // Matador Records OLE 158-1 // 1996.  Signed by Tim Midgett, Andy Cohen, and Michael Dahlquist. "Firewater" was the Chicago by way of Seattle & Missoula band Silkworm's first for the Matador Records label.  The 16-song double LP was recorded by Steve Albini and is the band's first as a trio following the departure of original member Joel RL Phelps.  While clocking in at an hour in length, its 16 songs feature guitar work by Andy Cohen that would make J Mascis proud.  Just shy of a decade after its release, drummer Michael Dahlquist was tragically killed when a woman intentionally crashed into his car in a suicide attempt.  Two of his colleagues and fellow musicians employed at the audio equipment manufacturer Shure, John Click of the Returnables and Douglas Meis of The Dials, were also killed in the crash.  Following Dahlquist's passing, Tim Midgett (now professionally known as Midyett) and Andy Cohen formed the band Bottomless Pit with Chris Manfrin of Seam, releasing three excellent full length albums and an EP before disbanding in 2014.  Silkworm are the subject of the 2013 documentary film "Couldn't You Wait? The Story of Silkworm" which features interviews with Steve Albini, Stephen Malkmus of Pavement, Jeff Tweedy of Wilco and many more.  While the band never received the commercial success they so deserved, "Firewater," among other titles in their catalog, is a must own indie rock treasure.  They were a seriously great band.

Day 17 :: Something found in or written on the sleeve :: John Lennon & Yoko Ono ~ Double Fantasy:: My dad was the biggest Beatles fan and he had a few records that survived his collection and this was one. My uncle passed away before I was able to get to know him but this record was in my fathers collection and years later I obtained it. It wasn't until a year after my father passed that I noticed this writing on the back of the record. My uncle had left a little message and I didn't even notice until a few weeks ago. Music keeps us connected even when the ones we loved have passed on. #mayvinylchallenge

Halfway into the #mayvinylchallenge & today it's "A Nostalgic Record". I decided to go deep into the memory bank with something from my childhood: 1999's "Sigur Rós - Ágætis Byrjun". The way I discovered Sigur Rós was once again by watching waaay to many music videos on TV. In early 2000 the video for "Svefn-g-englar" was repeatedly on Swedish television & they got some well deserved radio airtime too. I had only listened to music where the lyrics were either in Swedish or English before & even though the Icelandic language comes from the same family of languages as Swedish it's almost impossible to understand what the lyrics are about if you just hear them (& some parts of the album is actually just gibberish). Sigur Rós "forced" me to listen to music in a completely different way & really view the human voice as an instrument as much as a guitar, piano etc. This is something I carry with me all the time & something I'll be forever grateful for. What was your first encounter with Sigur Rós? #sigurros #agaetisbyrjun #1999
